	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Fish consumption reaches all-time high</h1>

			
			<h4>
												12 March 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>At the occasion of the 29th session of FAO Committee on Fisheries, the biennial publication <i>The State of the World's Fisheries and Aquaculture</i>&nbsp;was released.</p><p>It shows that total world production of fish and fish products rose from 140 million tonnes in 2007 to 145 million tonnes in 2009. Fish products continue to be the most-traded of food commodities, worth a record US$102 billion in 2008, up by 9% from 2007. The contribution of fish to global diets has reached a record of about 17 kg per person on average, supplying over three billion people with at least 15% of their average animal protein intake. People have never eaten as much fish and more people than ever are employed in or depend on the sector. Overall, fisheries and aquaculture support the livelihoods of an estimated 540 million people, or 8% of the world population.</p><p>The report examines selected issues in fisheries and aquaculture, including fisheries-sector transparency, and trade measures against illegal, unreported and unregulated (IUU) fishing. Such trade measures are meant to block entry of such fish and fish products from international trade in an effort to better manage the entire fisheries sector and reduce levels of overexploitation.</p><p>The report insists also that the increasing demand for fish highlights the need for the sustainable management of aquatic resources. The report recommends an ecosystem approach to fisheries, which is an integrated approach for balancing societal objectives with the state of the fishery and its natural and human environment.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>
<i>FAO Media Centre, </i>press release, 31 January 2011<br/>

<a href="http://www.fao.org/news/story/en/item/50260/icode/" target="_self">http://www.fao.org/news/story/en/item/50260/icode/</a><br/>
FAO report, <i>The State of World Fisheries and Aquaculture 2010</i><br/>
<a href="http://www.fao.org/docrep/013/i1820e/i1820e00.htm" target="_self">http://www.fao.org/docrep/013/i1820e/i1820e00.htm</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Although global in scope, this report highlights various elements which should be taken into account by ACP countries in the elaboration of their development strategy for fisheries and aquaculture. First of all, it confirms the importance of fish as a source of food and livelihoods, as well as the importance of international fish markets – fish products being the most-traded food products. It also underlines the growing importance of potential non-tariff barriers, including the trade measures taken to stop IUU fishing, as well as the need for states, in order to benefit from international trade opportunities, to seriously tackle fisheries management issues, including the need for better transparency in how the access to resources is managed and allocated.</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
	</article>

